# Grug Brained Developer

Complexity is the apex predator. Every decision should reduce it.

## Say No

- Default answer to new features, abstractions, and indirection is **"no"**.
- If forced to say yes, build the **80/20 solution**: 80% of the value with 20% of the code. Skip the bells and whistles.

## Factor Late, Not Early

- Don't abstract too early — the system's shape hasn't emerged yet.
- Wait for **cut points**: narrow interfaces that trap complexity behind a small surface area.
- Bias toward waiting. Wrong abstractions are worse than duplication.
- Prototypes force reality — use them to discover structure before committing to architecture.

## Chesterton's Fence

- Understand code before removing or rewriting it, no matter how ugly it looks.
- If you can't explain why something exists, you don't have permission to delete it.

## Expression Complexity

- Break complex conditionals into named intermediate variables — easier to debug, easier to read.

```python
# ❌ Dense
if contact and not contact.is_active() and (contact.in_group(FAMILY) or contact.in_group(FRIENDS)):
    ...

# ✅ Grug
contact_is_inactive = not contact.is_active()
contact_is_family_or_friends = contact.in_group(FAMILY) or contact.in_group(FRIENDS)
if contact and contact_is_inactive and contact_is_family_or_friends:
    ...
```

## DRY — With Balance

- Respect DRY, but simple repeated code is often better than a complex abstraction to eliminate it.
- Duplication is far cheaper than the wrong abstraction.

## Locality of Behavior

- Put code on the thing that does the thing. When you look at it, you should know what it does.
- Spreading logic across many files for "separation of concerns" often just hides behavior.

## Testing

- Integration tests are the sweet spot: high-level enough to verify correctness, low-level enough to debug.
- Write most tests after prototyping, when the code has firmed up — but be disciplined about actually writing them.
- Reproduce bugs with a regression test first, then fix.
- Avoid mocking unless absolutely necessary; when needed, mock at coarse-grained boundaries only.

## Logging

- Log generously, especially logical branches (`if`/`for`).
- Include request IDs so logs can be grouped across services.
- Dynamic log levels (per-user if possible) are invaluable for production debugging.

## Refactoring

- Keep refactors small — the larger the refactor, the more likely it fails.
- The system should keep working at every step. Never be "too far from shore."
- Introducing more abstraction during a refactor is a warning sign, not progress.

## Concurrency

- Fear it. Prefer simple models: stateless request handlers, independent job queues.

## Optimizing

- Never optimize without a real profiling result showing the specific bottleneck.
- Network calls dwarf CPU — minimize them first.
- Premature optimization is the root of all evil.

## Generics and Closures

- Use sparingly, like salt. Small amount goes a long way; too much ruins everything.
- Limit generics to container-like classes where they add clear value.

## APIs

- Design for the caller, not the implementation.
- Layer APIs: simple API for common cases, complex API for complex cases.
- Put the API on the thing — don't make callers convert, wrap, or collect just to do something basic.

## Tools

- Invest time learning tools — two weeks of tool learning often doubles productivity.
- A good debugger is worth more than shiney rocks. Learn conditional breakpoints, expression evaluation, stack navigation.

## No FOLD (Fear Of Looking Dumb)

- Say "this is too complex" out loud. It gives others permission to admit confusion too.
- Complexity thrives when everyone pretends to understand.
